  <h1 class="CASENAME"><span class="RespondentName">LITTLE, WINFIELD E., JR.</span><br />
   <span class="dbno">95-DB-009</span> (<span class="Date">01/31/1996</span>) <span class="Misconduct">Fees</span> 
  <span class="Sanction">Reprimand</span> </h1>

  <p class="headingstyle">DISCIPLINARY BOARD</p>

  <p class="headingstyle"><span class="Creator">LOUISIANA STATE BAR ASSOCIATION</span></p>

  <p class="headingstyle">NO: 95-DB-009</p>

  <p class="headingstyle">IN RE: Winfield E. Little, Jr.</p>

  <p class="headingstyle">DISCIPLINARY BOARD RULING</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">On January 24, 1994, a complaint was filed with the office of Disciplinary Counsel alleging that
  respondent charged a fee exceeding the percentages set forth in the Louisiana Workers' Compensation provisions.  The
  complainant appealed a dismissal of the charge by Disciplinary Counsel, and a panel of the Disciplinary Board
  remanded the matter to Disciplinary Counsel for the filing of formal charges.  Formal charges were filed on March 24,
  1995, and a hearing was held before <span class="cite"><a href="../HC/1995-08-24_95-DB-009.htm">Hearing Committee No.
  5</a></span> on July 12, 1995. Hearing Committee No. 5 issued its findings and recommendation on August 23, 1995, and
  this matter was argued before the Disciplinary Board on October 19, 1995.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">The thoroughly considered and well-written findings and recommendations of Hearing Committee No.
  5 are approved and hereby form the basis for the Disciplinary Board's ruling of a public reprimand for respondent. 
  Mr. Little contractually agreed with his client to obtain a contingent fee on part of a recovery from a work related
  accident and a workers' compensation statutory fee for the remaining part of any recovery.  It is undisputed that
  respondent obtained an outstanding result for his client, but in doing so he retained a fee in excess of the
  statutory boundaries set forth in La.  R.S. 23:1141(B).  It is clear that respondent violated Rule
  <span class="Rules">1.5(c)</span> of the Rules of Professional Conduct.  He accepted a contingent fee in a workers'
  compensation case which exceeded the percentages set forth in the statute and therefore was prohibited by law.  The
  Hearing Committee weighed the aggravating and mitigating factors, referred to the ABA Standard For Imposing Lawyer
  Sanctions (1996) and the Louisiana cases and concluded that the appropriate sanction for respondent was a public
  reprimand.  Respondent remained recalcitrant throughout the hearing denying that he had done anything wrong and that
  the fee arrangement was customary in his region of the state.  The Disciplinary Board affirms the Hearing Committee
  recommendation.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">There is an ongoing dispute whether or not respondent has repaid his client, Kenneth McKinney,
  all of the fees that he withheld, plus interest and costs.  A civil suit was filed by the client and reached the
  Louisiana 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals, and that litigation is in the final stages of enforcement and collection. 
  Respondent has repaid his client the vast majority of the fees and costs, and the remaining amount allegedly due
  consists largely of interest for the period of time respondent held the excessive fees and costs.  The matter of
  resolving any remaining fees and costs due is best left to the civil lawsuit since inadequate evidence was presented
  to the Hearing Committee and the Disciplinary Board to include any amounts due in a recommended sanction.  McKinney
  can be made whole through the usual civil proceedings.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">For the reasons set forth herein, the Disciplinary Board publically reprimands respondent and
  assesses all costs of these proceedings unto him.</p>

  <p class="Bodycopy">This ruling approved this 29th day of January, 1996.</p>

